Quick guide#

Model checkpoints and electrophysiology data are uploaded to Drive here. Checkpoints are provided for all four models examined in this study: cNVAE, VAE, cNAE, and AE. Please refer to Table 2 in the main text for details.

To load a model:

from base.utils_model import load_model_lite
trainer = load_model_lite('./cNVAE/')[0]
print(trainer.model)

Below scripts can be used to create ROFL datasets, train unsupervised models on them, and fit MT neurons to the pretrained models. The scripts can be found in the /scripts.

Generating ROFL datasets#

To generate 1000 frames for each of the ROFL categories utilized in the main paper, run the following:

./create_data.sh 1000 1000 17

Training VAEs#

Train a VAE on the fixate-1 dataset, using the first GPU and a \(\beta\) value of 0.15:

./fit_vae.sh fixate1 cuda:0 --kl_beta 0.15

The model checkpoint (trained for 160 epochs) for this is provided in the cNVAE folder in the shared Drive (link).

Ridge regression#

Use a pretrained model to fit MT neurons:

./fit_neuron.sh <model_name> <fit_name> <device>

Electrophysiology data#

The neural data used in this study (DATA.h5, also on Drive) contains responses of \(N=141\) MT neurons to naturalistic motion stimuli. A subset of these neurons (\(N=84\)) have been previously deposited on crcns.org under the name mt1. The remaining 57 neurons are not yet publicly available online. We are planning to make the remaining neurons available online upon publication.

# path = results_dir()
# path = pjoin(tmp_dir, 'trainer_analysis')
path = pjoin(tmp_dir, 'neural_analysis')

for src in os.listdir(path):
    parts = src.split('_')
    try:
        i = next(
            i for i, e in
            enumerate(parts)
            if 'beta' in e
        )
    except StopIteration:
        print(f"skipped: {src}\n")
        continue
    beta = parts[i].split('-')[1]
    beta = f"beta-{float(beta)}"
    dst = '_'.join([
        beta if i == j else e for
        j, e in enumerate(parts)
    ])
    if src != dst:
        os.rename(
            src=pjoin(path, src),
            dst=pjoin(path, dst),
        )
        print(f"src = {src},\ndst = {dst}\n")

len(sorted(os.listdir(path)))
